Subject: Fix import on Python < 3.9 (TypeError: 'type' object is not subscriptable)

whois/parser.py, whois/whois.py and whois/__init__.py use builtin
generics as runtime-evaluated type annotations (list[str],
dict[str, str], dict[str, Any], tuple[...]), which only work
natively on Python >= 3.9. On older interpreters (e.g. Python 3.6
on SLE/Leap 15.7) importing the package fails with:

    TypeError: 'type' object is not subscriptable

Upstream's own fix for this (commits c81c72c and 37172db,
"from __future__ import annotations") does not help here: that
future feature was only added in Python 3.7, so it raises
"SyntaxError: future feature annotations is not defined" on
Python 3.6, breaking the import just as badly.

Instead, replace the builtin generics with their typing module
equivalents (List, Dict, Tuple), which have supported subscripting
since Python 3.5 and work unmodified on every supported version.

diff -ru a/whois/__init__.py b/whois/__init__.py
--- a/whois/__init__.py
+++ b/whois/__init__.py
@@ -6,7 +6,7 @@
 import socket
 import subprocess
 import sys
-from typing import Any, Optional, Pattern
+from typing import Any, Dict, List, Optional, Pattern
 
 from .exceptions import WhoisError
 from .parser import WhoisEntry
@@ -25,13 +25,13 @@
     command: bool = False,
     flags: int = 0,
     executable: str = "whois",
-    executable_opts: Optional[list[str]] = None,
+    executable_opts: Optional[List[str]] = None,
     inc_raw: bool = False,
     quiet: bool = False,
     ignore_socket_errors: bool = True,
     convert_punycode: bool = True,
     timeout: int = 10,
-) -> dict[str, Any]:
+) -> Dict[str, Any]:
     """
     url: the URL to search whois
     command: whether to use the native whois command (default False)
